Let's figure out the range of the function  $f(x) = \sqrt{x^2}$.

Think about what happens when you square a number and then take its square root.  Since squaring any real number always gives you a non-negative result, the square root of that squared number will also always be non-negative.

This means our function can output any non-negative real number.

So the range is:

\begin{align*}
\boxed{[0, \infty)}
\end{align*}

